<title>History of Computing</title>
</head>
<body>

<h3>"It Weaves Algebraic Patterns": Abacuses, Looms, and Arithmetic
Engines (c.3000 B.C. to c.1870)</h3> 

The need for counting has always been with us: trade and barter, sizing
up the enemy's army, 
describing the size of a herd, economic planning (the
Egyptians had sophisticated harvesting timetables).  This ubiquitous
need led to the Sumerian
counting tablet using small stones (<i>calculi</i>), the Chinese abacus,
and numeration systems (who invented the zero?).  Social and economic
development after the Dark Ages brought the need for more complicated
and time-consuming computations: multiplication and division, raising to
powers, taking roots.  Inventors responded with the logarithms, Napier's
Bones, and the slide rule (an early analog computer); and with various
mechanical calculating machines, culminating in the dazzlingly complex
designs of the eccentric genius Charles Babbage and his protege Ada Lovelace.
Babbage's insight, inspired by Jacquard's punch-card-controlled weaving
loom, was that machines could be made to perform an <i>arbitrary</i>
sequence of manipulations of numerical quantities: the genesis of the
<i>stored program</i> concept.  

