** 50s-60s, IBM and 7 dwarfs, early production computers,
transistorization, IC's, minis

   50s-mid 60s: "IBM and the 7 Dwarfs"; IBM 701; core memory (1951);
       transistorized Univac (1956); Univac I predicts election (1952 -
       get video!); FORTRAN compiler (1957); semiconductor IC Kilby at
       TI, Noyce at Fairchild (1958); Bell's modem  (1958)
** PEOPLE: Kilby, Noyce
** ANECDOTES: company mergers, etc; IBM strategy

** IC's enable minicomputers and supercomputers.  PDP-1, first commercial
       computer with mon & kbd (1960); PDP-8 1965;
       Multics 1965; Intel incorporated 1968; CDC 6600 and 7600,
       designed by S. Cray; Unix (Ritchie and Thompson) 1970; Xerox PARC
       est. 1970
** PEOPLE: Cray, Noyce/Moore, Ken Olsen

------

<h3>Not Just for Number Crunching Anymore</h3>

As computers became more powerful, people began to think of new ways of
using them, completely unlike the "number crunching" for which they were
originally intended.  Steve Russell, a graduate student at MIT,
demonstrated the archetype of all video games, Pong, in 1962.  Doug
Engelbart invented the mouse in 1964, just one year after
Ivan Sutherland had demonstrated Sketchpad, the first use of computer
graphics.  The proliferation of computer <i>programming languages</i>
used for these tasks (BASIC, FORTRAN and COBOL, to name three of the
most popular) caused people to realize that programming computers was as
substantial a discipline as building them.  The design of programming
languages, programs, <i>algorithms</i> for solving problems, and the
<i>data structures</i> on which they operated, quickly became a field in
its own right, based on the earlier theoretical work of the genius Alan
Turing.  In 1968, the NATO Science Committee Conference coined the term
<i>software engineering</i> and the new field was officially born.

1967-68 Knuth algorithms/data
structures;

