<h3>The Apotheosis of Mechanical Computers</h3>
d37 21
a57 22
It was the late 1800's.  The U.S. was the world's industrial and
economic leader, its capitalist ambience encouraged an unprecedented
wave of innovation and invention....and the population was growing so
fast that tabulation of census results was barely complete by the time
the next census came around.  It was in this atmosphere that the
energetic and entrepreneurial Herman Hollerith filed for patents on his
punch-card reader and tabulating machine, which the U.S. Government
would use for the census from 1890 until ??? and which made Hollerith a
millionaire.  Meanwhile, among the calculator builders improving on the
work of their nineteenth-century forefathers, we find one who would be
pivotal: Konrad Zuse's machines could be programmed using paper tapes,
and operated using the binary (base 2) number system and the logic
invented by George Boole in 1854.  Unfortunately for Zuse, another
machine stole the show: the Mark I, built at Harvard and IBM under the
direction of Mark Aiken, the ultimate programmable mechanical
computer---and a technological dead end.  For in rural Iowa, the ideas
behind the nearest predecessor to today's electronic computer were being
developed. The inventors would deliver to
the military the next-generation electronic computer and launch a new
industry, only to be overtaken by the company that soon became
synonymous with computers: IBM, the descendant of Hollerith's
Computing-Tabulating-Recording Company.
